"Leonelli G., Pelfini M., Cella U.M.D., Garavaglia V.","Climate warming and the recent treeline shift in the european alps: The role of geomorphological factors in high-altitude sites",2011,"Ambio","40","3",,"264","273",,,10.1007/s13280-010-0096-2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79955112444&partnerID=40&md5=ffd02cb8867edbe33615804d1b5325f5","Earth Sciences Department, University of Milan, Via Mangiagalli 34, 20133 Milan, Italy; Department of Geomorphology and Physical Geography, University of Milan, Via Mangiagalli 34, 20133 Milan, Italy; ARPA Valle d'Aosta, Loc. Grande Charrière 44, 11020 Saint Christophe, Italy; Department of Earth Sciences, University of Milan, Via Mangiagalli 34, 20133 Milan, Italy","Leonelli, G., Earth Sciences Department, University of Milan, Via Mangiagalli 34, 20133 Milan, Italy; Pelfini, M., Department of Geomorphology and Physical Geography, University of Milan, Via Mangiagalli 34, 20133 Milan, Italy; Cella, U.M.D., ARPA Valle d'Aosta, Loc. Grande Charrière 44, 11020 Saint Christophe, Italy; Garavaglia, V., Department of Earth Sciences, University of Milan, Via Mangiagalli 34, 20133 Milan, Italy","Abstract Global warming and the stronger regional temperature trends recently recorded over the European Alps have triggered several biological and physical dynamics in high-altitude environments. We defined the present treeline altitude in three valleys of a region in the western Italian Alps and reconstructed the past treeline position for the last three centuries in a nearly undisturbed site by means of a dendrochronological approach. We found that the treeline altitude in this region is mainly controlled by human impacts and geomorphological factors. The reconstruction of the altitudinal dynamics at the study site reveals that the treeline shifted upwards of 115 m over the period 1901-2000, reaching the altitude of 2505 m in 2000 and 2515 m in 2008. The recent treeline shift and the acceleration of tree colonization rates in the alpine belt can be mainly ascribed to the climatic input. However, we point out the increasing role of geomorphological factors in controlling the future treeline position and colonization patterns in high mountains. © Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences 2010.","Climate change; European Alps; Geomorphology; Larix decidua; Tree rings; Treeline","acceleration; altitude; colonization; deciduous tree; dendrochronology; environmental factor; geomorphology; global warming; mountain region; restoration ecology; temperature effect; tree ring; treeline; Alps; Italy; Larix; Larix decidua",,,,,,"Ali, A.A., Carcaillet, C., Guendon, J.-L., Quinif, Y., Roiron, P., Terral, J.-F., The Early Holocene treeline in the southern French Alps: New evidence from travertine formations (2003) Global Ecology and Biogeography Letters, 12 (5), pp. 411-419; Applequist, M.B., A simple pith locator for use with off-center increment cores (1958) Journal of Forestry, 56, p. 141; Böhm, R., Jones, P.D., Hiebl, J., Frank, D., Brunetti, M., Maugeri, M., The early instrumental warm-bias: A solution for long central European temperature series 1760-2007 (2010) Climatic Change, 101, pp. 41-67; Brunetti, M., Maugeri, M., Monti, F., Nanni, T., Temperature and precipitation variability in Italy in the last two centuries from homogenised instrumental time series (2006) International Journal of Climatology, 26 (3), pp. 345-381. , DOI 10.1002/joc.1251; Burga, C.A., Vegetation history and palaeoclimatology of the Middle Holocene: Pollen analysis of alpine peat bog sediments, covered formerly by the Rutor Glacier, 2510 m (Aosta Valley, Italy) (1991) Global Ecology and Biogeography Letters, 1, pp. 43-150; Butler, D.R., Malanson, G.P., Resler, L.M., Walsh, S.J., Wilkerson, F.D., Schmid, G.L., Sawyer, C.F., Geomorphic patterns and processes at alpine treeline (2009) The Changing Alpine Treeline, 12, pp. 63-84. , ed. D. Butler, G. Malanson, S. Walsh, S. Fagre,Amsterdam: Elsevier; Caccianiga, M., Andreis, C., Armi